></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Life</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Keeping traditional Malay music alive</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>A new festival at the Esplanade, Gemadah, aims to showcase how traditional Malay music practitioners are not only keeping the art alive in Singapore, but are also injecting innovative ideas into the genre.</Para><Para>Taking place at various venues at the arts centre on Saturday, the festival will feature mostly free performances, as well as workshops and talks.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>There is a growing number of traditional Malay musicians in Singapore and they are in demand at events such as weddings and cultural performances, notes Esplanade programmer Fezhah Maznan.</Para><Para>"We wanted to create a public platform to bring these musicians, young and old, together to encourage artistic exchange and knowledge-sharing, as well as to help them build new audiences here."</Para><Para>She adds: "It is important that we not only celebrate our music heritage, but also create new material that is representative of the times and present sounds for the future."</Para><Para>Rentas, the only ticketed show, will feature new compositions as well as re-arrangements of traditional Malay music by composer/ musicians Syafiqah 'Adha Sallehin and Megat Firdaus - two rising names in the scene here.</Para><Para>Both were mentored by the National Arts Council's Young Artist Award winner Riduan Zalani through Rentas, a one-month residency programme.</Para><Para>*</Para><Para>BOOK IT / GEMADAH</Para><Para>WHERE: Various venues within the Esplanade, 1 Esplanade Drive</Para><Para>WHEN: Saturday, from 10am</Para><Para>ADMISSION: Free, except for Rentas ($15 from Sistic, go to <ELink type="webpage" ref="http://www.sistic.com.sg">www.sistic.com.sg</ELink> or call 6348-5555)</Para><Para>INFO: For programme details, go to tinyurl.com/yc582rhg</Para><Para>Syafiqah, 28, says: "I'm honoured to be working with my contemporaries in the traditional Malay music scene in creating new music compositions that traverse the traditional Malay music soundscapes and, at the same time, pushing the boundaries of traditional Malay music performance.</Para><Para>"Although the performers in Rentas come from differing musical backgrounds, everyone is equally passionate in contributing his talents and ideas towards a unifying work."</Para><Para>The 8pm performance is sold out, but there are still tickets available for the 2pm show.</Para><Para>In assembling the musicians and programmes for Gemadah, the Esplanade worked with Ariffin Abdullah, founder of renowned Singapore-based Malay music ensemble Sri Mahligai, and his team from the Traditional Malay Music Consortium.</Para><Para>Syafiqah will also conduct a workshop centred on the accordion's role in traditional Malay music. In another masterclass, veteran musician Azrin Abdullah will impart lessons on the oud, a string instrument.</Para><Para>Scene stalwart Zubir Abdullah will give a talk on the evolution of Malay music and its impact around the world, while Dr Larry Francis Hilarian, a music consultant at the National Institute of Education, will discuss Malay music and culture.</Para><Para>The festival culminates in a free evening show - Gala Gemadah - at the Esplanade Outdoor Theatre at 9pm.</Para><Para>It will feature prominent composers, arrangers and musicians, such as Al Hafiz Jamat, Aidil Akmal, Azrin, Dzul Rabull Jalil and Fadhli Ramlee, who will perform Malay music genres such as inang, ghazal and zapin.</Para><Para>Initiatives like the festival can help bring in new audiences.</Para><Para>"We hope everyone will be able to appreciate and look towards this festival for innovative, fresh and engaging quality traditional Malay music in Singapore."</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Eddino Abdul Hadi </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Composer/musician Syafiqah 'Adha Sallehin will conduct a workshop centred on the accordion's role in traditional Malay music. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

